05272nam a22007695i 9780812202458DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132005pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979576336  a97808122024587 a10.9783/97808122024582doi  a(DE-B1597)449103  a(OCoLC)654304799  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0041502bisacsh04a795.09441 aKavanagh, Thomas M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDice, Cards, Wheels :bA Different History of French Culture /cThomas M. Kavanagh. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b2 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Authors and Issues00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Toward a Cultural History of Gambling -- t2. Dicing with the Saints: Jehan Bodel's Jeu de saint Nicolas -- t3. Getting God's Edge: Pascal's Gambler as Paraclete -- t4. The Libertine's Bluff -- t5. Gambling High and Low: Casanova's Story of My Life -- t6. Staging the Gambler: Sex, Sentiment, and Family Values -- t7. Gambling on the Anvil of History: Balzac's The Wild Ass)s Skin -- t8. Whist, or the Aristocracy of Mystery: Barbey d'Aurevilly's "Beneath the Cards in a Game of Whist" -- t9. Betting Against Your Self: Paul Bourget's ''A Gambler" -- t10. Dreaming the Casino: Demy's Baie des anges and Melville's Bob le fiambeur -- tConclusion -- tAppendix ''A Gambler″ -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGambling has been a practice central to many cultures throughout history. In Dice, Cards, Wheels, Thomas M. Kavanagh scrutinizes the changing face of the gambler in France over a period of eight centuries, using gambling and its representations in literature as a lens through which to observe French culture. Kavanagh argues that the way people gamble tells us something otherwise unrecognized about the values, conflicts, and cultures that define a period or class. To gamble is to enter a world traced out by the rules and protocols of the game the gambler plays. That world may be an alternative to the established order, but the shape and structure of the game reveal indirectly hidden tensions, fears, and prohibitions.Drawing on literature from the Middle Ages to the present, Kavanagh reconstructs the figure of the gambler and his evolving personae. He examines, among other examples, Bodel's dicing in a twelfth-century tavern for the conversion of the Muslim world; Pascal's post-Reformation redefinition of salvation as the gambler's prize; the aristocratic libertine's celebration of the bluff; and Balzac's, Barbey d'Aurevilly's, and Bourget's nineteenth-century revisions of the gambler.Dice, Cards, Wheels embraces the tremendous breadth of French history and emerges as a broad-ranging study of the different forms of gambling, from the dice games of the Middle Ages to the digital slot machines of the twenty-first century, and what those games tell us about French culture and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGambling in literature. 0aGamblingzFrancexHistory. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.1 aBourget, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220245840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9